<rate>5< /rate>< review>
It is perfectly priced especially for the quality of the food you get. Lets put it this way, you'll be full but you'd feel guilty leaving a crumb on your plate. IT'S THAT GOOD!!
Trust me, I've tried a lot on their menu and I've NEVER been disappointed. The place has an amazing ambiance. The waiters and friendly and the service is great. It's just an all around fantastic restaurant and I'd recommend it to anyone who likes their lunch/dinner to be perfect and satisfying.< /review>

The chicken kabak is also very moist and delicious. The shwarma's are well seasoned but slightly dryer than the chicken and kufta kabab. The Jerusalem salad is exceptional, juicy and bright. Overall, I really enjoyed this place</Review>

<user_id>101750658589025531050<//user_id>< Name>
shiva sharma<//Name>
< Time>
1534799981756</Time>
<rating>2<//rating><Review>Downgrading from 4 to 2 stars.

First the pros; the chicken shawarma is nicely seasoned and one of the better ones in the bay area. Their hummus is also pretty good.

The cons overshadow the pros though and I have no interest in wasting time here anymore.

Service is extremely slow regardless of when you come in. I've been the first customer through the door on weekdays and have had to wait 30 mins + to get my meal because they seem to prioritize any phone orders/catering and they simply don't have the manpower to deal with that. They'll have the same cashier running back and forth between prepping bags for to go orders and taking your order (while you're waiting in front of the cash register) in a very disorganized fashion. Happened about 3 times before I decided it's not worth coming here on weekdays because it really eats up your lunch hour.

On weekends they have a "brunch" buffet. In the past they've always allowed customers to choose between the buffet or ordering off the menu. The menu items are of slightly better quality usually; the chicken in the buffet is usually dry and the other meat option varies - can be fish or beef etc, and if you don't eat beef then you'd want to order off the regular menu. This last weekend we arrived at 11:55 am for lunch. This was 25 mins past their opening time of 11:30. First they told us we couldn't order off the regular menu. No idea if this is a new policy or they just decided on the spot to not accommodate us. The only option was to order the buffet, but their buffet wasn't ready (aside from the hummus and salad station).
So 25 mins after opening they're still not ready for buffet service, yet they'll give no option besides the buffet to customers? That's just laughably bad service.

They don't seem to care about their business, so why should I bother coming here again.< /Review>< pictures>
None</pictures>

< Review>
A wonderful Israeli style restaurant.  The new ownership are great but the restaurant is no longer strictly kosher.  If you don't require it, I would highly recommend.  I did speak with one of the owners who told me that they still to glatt kosher catering.

I highly recommend the Sabich, which is hard to find in the US.  It is a pita sandwich like falafel but it is filled with eggplant and hard boiled egg.  Also get the labne with zatar (thick yogurt with wild thyme and sesame seeds).  you won't regret it.< /Review>

< Review>
I thought this place was going to be terrible at first, but I was hungry so i went for it.  Let me tell you, it was one of the most exquisite culinary experiences I've ever had, and I don't give away 5 stars easily.  The waiters were extremely amiable and knowledgable of the menu, and helped me pick out the "Schnitzel" with a side of falafel.  The chicken was cooked to perfection, seasoned phenomenally.  Afterwards, I indulged in some "kunafa" and coffee, while I chatted to the owner, Hani, about Mediterranean food.  Definitely give this place a try, you won't regret it.< /Review>

The staff its great.

I have been a customer for 10 years of Eco Thrifty Store and this is the first time I have been asked to get up from a chair.

In the past 8 years Elders/disable had use those chairs to rest for 10 or 15 minutes and then continue their shopping personally know at least 45 disabled customers who need to take intermittent rests due to their chronic or medical needs. As a member of this community, it's important to know the places who are accessible and friendly to any person with a disability.

to all those who need to sit for a few minutes for now on let know the security guard to provide you with a chair as soon as you enter the door if you know, you may need to take a rest for a few minutes. This has been a great place Mark is a great "guy" Maria and other cashiers are fabulous.

A lovely bit of serenity with many plants and flowers to enjoy and purchase. Located near many wineries on an easy, paved road to get there. Bring a picnic lunch to share with your family in the safe of beautiful Oak trees while watching the ducks on the pond. They also have treats like ice cream and soda to purchase. Fun for the whole family.  In a word: Lovely.< /review>

< name>
Blanca Diaz Houle< /name>
< review>
Great selection of daylilies, pumpkins, a few other treats in the gift shop.</review>
</record></dataset><record>
< review>
OMG! This place is a MUST see!  The website does NOT do it justice. This Flower Farm is beautiful. The gift shop is very cute and the customer service is superb. Not only are the demonstration garden's beautiful the daylilies garden is nothing I have ever seen before..The picnic area is very quaint and peaceful and you sit along the pond.  You can see the Koi swim by, there are turtles and bull frogs in the pond as well..We did see a snake in the road by the gate, it was a harmless kings snake. We didn't bother it, it didn't bother us.  If you're looking for a nice day trip, it's definitely worth the drive. Prices are great! Nice selection of fruits, veggies, succulents and if course Lily's. Over 1200 varieties. Upon purchase they give you paperwork on how to keep your Lily's alive. I'm not exactly a green thumb.<//review>

<rating>5< /rating>< review>
This review is for the pumpkin patch only.  This is a wonderful place to bring the family and pick out a pumpkin or two for the Halloween season.  They have a nice picnic area, a fun corn maze, plus a great selection of pumpkins.  The best thing about this place?  It does not have the insane crowds of Apple Hill during the fall season.  This was our 4th year coming here and we plan to continue to come here.<//review>

< rate>

<text>A beautiful place to spend an afternoon. The flower gardens are amazing and make for a lovely stroll. There are picnic areas, gift shop, restrooms, and nursery. In October they have a fun pumpkin patch with a free corn maze. Pumpkins come in quite the variety of shapes, sizes, and types (traditional, Cinderella style, gourds, you name it, they have it). Very reasonable pricing on large pumpkins. We got quite the selection. Just love this place and its offerings.<//text><Pictures>None</Pictures>< Resp>

< Review>
I being my family here in all seasons. Lillies are their specialty.  In the spring it is a riot of color from all the lillies they have planted in the fields surrounding the property. The planted grounds are ideal to see what they are selling and how well they would do in your yard. The planted grounds are extensive, so you can take a long walk. In summer they feature all California varietals as well as perennials and annuals. The store changes with plant products for spring and summer and they have holiday items as well. This is just a great place for everyone.< /Review>

< Review>
The staff at the Manhattan Beach WeWork office are extremely friendly and inviting especially Bri. Bri was the first to great me with enthusiasm and was very accommodating and professional while providing a tour of the office space. <text>They saved Mango's life.
Mango was diagnosed with lymphoma at another clinic and quickly went downhill after his Elspar injection.  He could barely stand.  At 14 we thought his little body couldn't handle any more and we feared the worst when we brought him here.
The staff was calming and professional and most important they kept us constantly informed so we were never left wondering what was going on.
After his first night here we came to visit in the outside tent. Honestly I thought it would be our last visit. He was so weak. But the staff was optimistic so that gave us hope.
Two emotionally grueling days later we picked him up and brought him home.. and he's walking! The turnaround is incredible.
We know our time with him is short with his lymphoma but we feel he's on a better path thanks to the guidance we're getting.
This has been a difficult journey but I'm glad for the quality help, advice and expertise. I'm sure Mango would be thankful too.< /text>< Gmap_id>

< Review>
I took my dog here when he was suddenly unable to walk. I thought he might be having a stroke or seizure. They took my dog in right away and called me quickly with the diagnosis (vestibular disease, basically vertigo for dogs). The doctor explained everything thoroughly and I was pleasantly surprised  that he did not pressure me to get more tests. In fact, we asked him to do a blood test just in case. (They were clear as he said they probably would be).The person at the front desk was patient and helpful, even though I know she had many other stressed out people she was dealing with. I was very impressed with the professionalism and communication. Also I expected the price to be much higher since it was an emergency situation. I was pleasantly surprised that it was pretty much in line with what I would pay at any vet. Lower than some even.</Review>

< Text>
This review is specifically for the oncology dept and my absolutely devastating and frustrating experience. We regrettably decided to work with this hospital when our dog was diagnosed with cancer as they were local and convenient. I can‚Äôt help but wonder if our dog would still be alive today or would‚Äôve had more time with us had we worked with a vet hospital with an ounce of compassion or communication.

From the beginning, they were extremely disorganized, and the lack of follow up in a timely matter for such a critical situation was unacceptable. We were first scheduled a surgeon consult to remove a mass, later told we actually needed to schedule an oncology consult for a ct scan. After spending thousands of dollars in diagnostics, we were told the dr would call us that evening as with covid we had no contact with the oncologist. Now, if she had called us or emailed or followed up within that week it would‚Äôve been nice. But no, I had to call, leave voicemails, put in notes with front desk, send emails...when you are heart broken and have no idea if your dog is dying it isn‚Äôt really the time to leave owners in the dark for 10 days about the prognosis or treatment options.

We did finally get in touch with the dr, who deemed the tumor inoperable, which is understandable and we were on board to begin treatment. We were *not* told that we needed monthly bloodwork, what side affects to look out for, that it is recommended to do regular urinalysis, any possible drug interactions, or any follow up whatsoever in terms of guidance of what to expect, what is next. When we called, emailed, trying to figure out how to get a refill of our dogs chemo, we were first asked if we had been seeing another oncologist and if we wanted to schedule a CT scan (??? Hello, we already paid $4000 for that AT YOUR CLINIC) and later was told she needs bloodwork to continue chemo. News to us! I called to schedule an appt with oncology dept within minutes, and front desk accidentally scheduled the blood draw with the wrong dept. They were apparently unable to internally ask the other dept which blood panels to run for her, so they canceled our appt day of. Then you have to wait days until they check their email or voicemail. Our regular vet clinic was furious and had to call into PESCM to demand that they somehow fit us into their ‚Äúbusy schedule‚Äù as their patient needs their CANCER TREATMENT. That worked!

Of the 4 months between discovering our dogs mass and the day that she died, I must have spent 6 weeks calling, emailing, trying to get through to the unresponsive dr and oncology team, lapse of treatment, trying to schedule appointments, being told over and over how under staffed they were. Sure, I get it. Pandemic has been rough on us all, and running a vet hospital is not easy. But have some compassion and refer your clients out if you don‚Äôt have the time or ability to treat them. Suddenly one day our dog collapsed, I called into the vet hospital asking what to do. She had just been in 3 days prior and blood work apparently came back normal. I was told by front desk they would call the oncologist and she would get back to us same day. Our dog died hours later. The oncologist never once called us or followed up. Our vet was mortified that the clinic didn‚Äôt recommend to do a urinalysis to check for blood in her urine given the situation.

I thought it was so sweet that we received sympathy cards from our regular vet clinic and the pharmacy that provided her cancer treatment...and literally couldn‚Äôt even get a call or email back from the oncologist treating our dog the day that she suddenly collapsed. Which, of course comes as no surprise...given the lack of compassion throughout the entire time that she was a patient of theirs.

I hate to leave this negative and long winded review, as the front desk and staff has always been extremely kind and helpful to us. I don‚Äôt know if we were just an off case that slipped through the cracks...but I sincerely hope they find a solution to whatever went wrong so that other owners don‚Äôt experience the same.</Text>

< Text>
Profit first, animal care second. My heart is broken.

Be kind both ways during an emergency: staff to clients and clients to staff. Both are under extreme stress. Staff have more information as they are inside of the building, but are not emotionally invested in outcomes. Clients sit in cars with little to no insight. Due to COVID clients are no longer treated as partners in care.

Since 2018, I have spent $18,814.81 (photo included) over 46 visits. At no time have Pet ERs been so overwhelmed & GPs & staff so burned out. Still, there are ways to help clients & deescalate stressful situations.

Yesterday, H (7 mos) was hit by an SUV at 4:30pm. I rushed to PESCM & was told a nurse would come get H & sit tight in the lot, but 3hrs later they admitted they had forgotten us.

It's been more than a year since clients could meet with DRs & sit with their animals during a crisis. What is normal for the staff who have visibility is a black hole of fear for a client sitting in the dark for hours in their car.

Close to 10pm Dr. Ng called. H had not been treated for pain. Dr. Ng wanted to run an expensive blood test, so she could give H pain medication known to cause liver damage instead of using gabapentin. This was not a solution, it was designed to increase the bill & put H to sleep as they delayed X-rays.

I was scared, stressed, & still processing losing two senior dogs in traumatic middle-of-the-night crisis situations at PESCM 4 weeks ago.

Dr. Ng said didn't have time to talk about gabapentin. I was transferred to provide my credit card details. The quote included additional medications that hadn't been discussed & no one could explain them to me.

In the confusion, I started to melt down with frustration & panic. I don't believe this would have happened pre-COVID in-person. The discussion was circular, unproductive, & stressful. Leah, Avery, and Taylor decided they did not want to treat H, because I was in too much distress. Avery said they would keep H overnight for $60, but threatened if H went into crisis no one would intervene as she died, hanging up on me.

They staff have hard jobs, but in COVID at this location the evening staff don't appear to see clients are struggling too. Avery & Taylor did not appear equipped with compassion for looking at the situation from a client's experience of being left in the dark, forgotten among other emergencies, having to be financially careful. I also recently went through two traumatic deaths at PESCM.

February 12, 2021

Lucy, 14 yo, treated by Dr. Sablock & Dr. Harb died without dignity.

Dr. Harb spent 10 hours @ $900 running tests/observation. Her recommendation for a senior dog showing signs of cognitive decline (nasal cancer had become brain cancer), only able to walk in a circle, leaning to one side, stuck at walls was "buy a snuffle mat." Two days later, Feb 12, 2021, Lucy was rushed to the ER at 2:30am. The ER night doctor conveyed, "Dr. Harb doesn't like giving bad news. I see a lot of Dr. Harb's patients in the middle of the night in a crisis."
--
Paisley, 15 yo pug (Lucy's sister), regularly treated by Dr. Harb and Dr. Zarfoss. Paisley also died without dignity, crying out, scared, & soaked in urine.

12 days after Lucy died, Paisley had a midnight seizure. The ER was understaffed and the techs wouldn't allow me to hold her in my car for the three hours of wait time.

Instead, Paisley was taken inside, forgotten, & crated for the last three hours of her life alone, cold, & left in a bed soaked with her urine. Per night-time COVID policy, I was only allowed to see Paisley after she was heavily sedated & catheterized for euthanasia. The towel she was wrapped in was wet with cold urine. She was drugged, dysphoric, & scared when she died.

This business has taken advantage of COVID to increase profits by being opaque and not meeting with clients. The default is to run up bills, which would have been less likely pre-COVID.

PESCM can do better to close the empathy gap, which would help everyone.<//Text>

<rate>5</rate>< review>
Dr. Bowie and staff fixed my girl!!!   I found PESCM via an online search a while ago. I recently visited PESCM for a 2nd emergency visit.   My dog had serious gastro-intestinal problems. PESCM was compassionate and caring for my girl.  I was given options of taking her home (and giving her iv fluids) or letting her stay and PESCM do that.  I opted for the stay at hospital option as they have staff onsite 24/7 (no animal is left alone overnight).  I was also able to call in and check with a nurse on my dog's condition which gave me some peace of mind. The price of the care was fair in price considering the nature of the business.   I highly recommend PESCM.</review>

Ours was a specialty visit. Besides being frail with kidney disease and recently diagnosed with hypothyroidism, my 16 yo Chihuahua, Pegasus, has vision loss in both eyes. <user>107830683917438399597</user>< Name>
Eugenia Hogan</Name>
<date>1544845756312</date><Rating>1<//Rating><text>UPDATE:
Came in today once again (now a month later) due to pain from the same infection/abscess site. They drained it once and packed it for me shortly after my previous review. I waited for authorization and am still waiting for the oral surgeon to be available to attend to the root canals I was told I needed. I understand there being a back log of patients as this is a clinic, but what I do NOT understand is waiting for over 40min and NOT being seen when I am in obvious pain. They did nothing for me. No exam, no questions, absolutely nothing. They WERE, however, very on top of getting my daughter's information entered into their system and doing an exam on HER so as to acquire a new patient. I am very disappointed, especially as I believe I was extremely understanding of the 30min-45min-1.5 hour long wait times each time I've gone in, and then again every they pulled me into the back room. I didn't mention being left in the chair and neglecting to numb me out, then numbing me and leaving me so long I had to be re-numbed two and three times, bc I figured that was due to the heavy patient load, and that's "just what you get at clinics." I am now being told that while Medi-Cal covers my root canals, it will NOT cover crowns.....but they HIGHLY recommend their in-house payment plans....at 17+% interest. NOT. Being told that prefab crowns are not covered is entirely contrary to what I found written on the Denti-Cal website. Apparently, given the numerous other reviews/updates just like mine now, this seems to be a pattern with Western Dental. Run far away. Run so very far, and run fast. If you don't believe me, check out their BBB complaints. I did. It's abysmal, to say the least. While Hilda, Sherein, Gloria, and Erica are phenomenal, I'm terrified at the thought of going back to this dental chop shop.

ORIGINAL POST:
Everyone here is absolutely stellar. Caring, compassionate staff all around. Came in Saturday due to pain because of a broken tooth and abscess. The x-ray tech was very gentle and understanding; he stopped twice to let me ride out the pain before continuing. Dr Sharma was very thorough in developing a game plan to knock everything out. Today, I got multiple fillings and a cleaning with Dr Beik; both she and Sherein inquired about my comfort at regular intervals. Sherein was very attentive, and Gloria(?) made sure I got answers to all my questions. Hilda was an absolute angel, watching my busy almost 3 y/o daughter, as negotiations for her care today fell through last minute. The wait time here may be longer than other places, but it is well worth it for the level of care and support these amazing people provide. I know I forgot names, but I'll definitely be back to learn them! Normal people do not have the luxury to take multiple days off work because you guys are incompetent. I should have been told when I arrived at 11:45. HORRIBLE customer service. No parking. Rude staff. Do yourself a favor and never go here
